snippet.textDisplay: Let me tell you a story that no one will care about.  Back in 2002 I was 20 years old and I went with a co-worker to go see a 95 Camaro SS at a dealership in Milwaukee which was an hour away from me.  I had the cash to buy the car outright.  I get to the dealership and the car was beautiful.  Black on black just awesome looking.  I go in to ask about it and the guy I talked to was a complete dick to me.  I can't remember what he said to me but he thought I was too young and wouldn't be serious about buying it.  He wouldn't even walk out to show me it or let me start it.  He was just an outright asshole.  I wanted a Camaro at that time and after that I couldn't find another Camaro like it so I started to look at mustangs.  I ended up buying a 95 mustang, which I still have btw and now I also have a 03 Mach 1.  Funny how that scenario played out back in 02 that changed what I was into it.

snippet.textDisplay:
The 4th Gen "Catfish" has frequently been called the "ugliest" Camaro, but I've never heard it called "the worst" (especially not with the LS1). Generally the 3rd Gens are stereotyped as "the worst," but I'd argue the late 2nd Gens have the least to offer.

I don't believe that aero comment is accurate. I'm not as familiar with the Camaro as I am the Firebird (and there are notable differences), but the 3rd Gen 'bird with the optional aero wheels had the lowest drag coefficient (0.29) of all the F-bodies; I'd wager that the 3rd Gen Camaro was capable of 'similar' stats (at least <0.32).

While the Pass Key IIs can fail, far more often, it's the cheap wiring in the key barrel that fails (not the key itself).

snippet.textDisplay: Dude you don't know your own vehicle very well. By 2001 the SS was all in house GM factory built, it was not sent to SLP as a Z28 to become an SS like older years. Matter of fact GM was still sending Firebird Formula and TransAm's to SLP to become WS6 or Firehawks, but was no longer doing the same with the SS. I bought my 1997 TransAm WS6 new, I was only 19yo and could barely afford it but the point is, I poured over the production details and articles of these cars, I was obsessed. All my paycheck was note/insurance. My point is, 20 years since I've owned an F-Body, and you don't know very much at all about that Era of f-body. Your video is has inaccuracies yet you felt the need to make a video that is less informative than the dealer brochure from the GM dealership I could get in 2000. No disrespect, enjoy your awesome car, but do more homework. The world doesn't need more bro science. ✌️

snippet.textDisplay: I actually had to pause the video bc i got so TILTED!.....I...... an owner and avid lover of F-Body Camaros (having had a v6 and a v8 of the year 2002) need to correct you. That original BADASS HOODSCOOP is indeed FUNCTIONAL (and is one of the easiest ways to tell from the fake hoods or replaced aftermarket WANNABES). That SICK BALD EAGLE AMERICAN hood scoop routes air 360 degrees from its point of origin and shoots it DIRECTLY into the the airbox. Take a look at 10:12 , pause it. You will notice the airbox in all its stock glory...with that badass "makes to much power" sticker on it. If you look carefully just below the front of the box you can see a rubber flap...THAT FLAP is a gasket that helps SEAL the RUSHING air into the airbox, IN FACT! If your car has given its graces of ownership to you.....you should still have a couple of FOAM gaskets installed FROM THE FACTORY under the hood where the AIR comes out...or they aren't there in which the cheap adhesive that GM used has caused them to fall off. Just above that rubber FLAP is a PERFECTLY ALLIGNED AMERICAN MONEY SLOT where the AIR is directed and pushed into the airbox. That is the most functional thing i can think of....unless we look at the WS6....those NOSTRILS are HUGE!

snippet.textDisplay: I think my first problem with the 90’s camaro is that from a design perspective it stayed in 90’s. It’s not like the classic 68’ mustang or 69 Pontiac gto which are although dated continue to inspire the designs of cars of today. I remember being a kid in the 90’s and early 00’s and like most kids, the 90’s Camaro was on my list of dream cars. Now when I see them on the road they look awkward and disproportioned. From a design perspective it’s like someone designed these cars to look futuristic, based on what they thought future cars would look like. As result by today’s standards it doesn’t look futuristic at all, instead it’s almost looks like a tv prop of a futuristic car from the 60’s. But that’s typical of many 90’s early 00’s cars imo. Looking back they should of just stuck with a more traditional design.
